nfluss der Emotionen auf die Wahrnehmung oder die Bedeutung der Narrativität für den Umgang mit Emotionalität bei sich und anderen, für Selbstbeherrschung und -therapie, aber auch Fremdkontrolle und Manipulation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCognition in literature. 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEuropean literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aKnowledge, Theory of, in literature. 4aAffektpoetik. 4aAufklärung, Europäische. 4aEmotionalität. 4aSentimentalismus. 4aWissen, emotionales. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aEmotion.  aemotional knowledge.  aenligthenment.  asentimentalism.1 aDickinson, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErdmann, Elisabeth von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrmann, Leonhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJekutsch, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKochetkova, Natalija D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoroliov, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoroliov, Sonja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKostin, Andrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinec, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReitzenstein, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorra-Mattenklott, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular